KoJen requests:
> 
> > Uh, KoJen, as Stella? pointed out with his original Black repeals,
> > we have *never* had workable proposal limits in this Game.
> 
> Let's try again, then. I would prefer something with 
> 
> 1) limit on total number of props submitted and/or up for vote.
> 
> 2) individual proposal limit per player.
> 
> 3) Waiving the per-player limit if the total number over all players is low.

All right, then:

PROTO-Proposal DB17 (Vanyel)
Proposal Limits
(Amends a Rule)

Amend [whatever the proposal rule is] to read:

Each Player shall have a Proposal queue.  Any time a Player sends a
Proposal to the Speaker, eir Proposal is added to eir queue.

In any Nomic Week no more than 30 Proposals may be up for Vote.  If there
are less than 30 Proposals in the Proposal queues of all Players, then all
will be cleared from their queues and added to the for-Vote queue.  If more
than 30 Proposals are sent to the Speaker, then e shall go through the
following process to determine which are added to the for-Vote queue:
     1)	E shall make a list of all Players in descending order by Honour.
     2)	E shall go through the list and remove all Players without any
	Proposals in eir queue.
     3) E shall go through the list in order, taking the first Proposal
	in the queue of each Player and adding it to the for-Vote queue
	until the for-Vote queue is full (30 Proposals).
     4) If the Speaker completes the list, having taken one Proposal from
	each Player's Proposal queue, e shall return to Step 2 and repeat.
After the Speaker has determined which Proposals would go in the for-Vote
queue, e shall post the Proposals in the queue to the Public Forum and
clear the for-Vote queue.

The only way a Proposal may be prematurely removed from a Player's 
Proposal Queue is if e, the Player, specifically requests such to the
Speaker.  The Player may not replace a Proposal with another; if e
removes it from the queue, all lower positions move up one to clear
the hole.  Such a removal is irrevocable.

In certain special cases, a Player may want a block of Proposals to 
be certain of being proposed at the same time; this may be done by
sending a message to the Speaker requesting to "Clump" certain Proposals.
These Proposals *must* be adjacent in the Player's Proposal queue.
In order to Clump Proposals, a Player must pay .5 Mark for 5 or less
Proposals or 1 Mark for 10 or less.  No Clumps may be of more than
10 Proposals.  If the Speaker has received more than 30 requests and
is cycling through the Player's queues, and he comes across one proposal
of a Clump, all Proposals in the Clump shall be moved to the for-Vote
queue, unless there are more than (30-(Number of Proposals in Clump))
Proposals already in the for-Vote queue, in which case *no* Proposals
from the Clump shall be added to the for-Vote queue.
***END PROTO

proposal history:
first proto 7 Oct 12:35 PM CDT

This takes care of all the problems I've noticed with limits.  (Oh, btw,
is 30 too steep?  I wasn't sure.)  Things to notice: All players should
get at least one proposal in; the players that miss out are the least
honourable ones (the honourable ones are more likely to propose beneficial
reform).  Proposals remain in a Player's Proposal Queue, unless they
request that they be removed.  "Clumps" enable packages to pass through
legislation.

Comments, questions?

> -- -- KoJen

Vanyel

