I like this, but I have a comment or two:

> ...
> In any Nomic Week no more than 30 Proposals may be up for Vote.

Actually it works out conveniently to have as many proposals as there
are registered players at the beginning of the week.  Otherwise if
we ever grow to 60 players we could easily have half the players
unable to propose.
 

> In order to Clump Proposals, a Player must pay .5 Mark for 5 or less
> Proposals or 1 Mark for 10 or less.  No Clumps may be of more than
> 10 Proposals.

Marks are too chaotic right now.  Let the payment be in points, and
let it be a flat 3 points per proposal, up to a limit of 10; and 
make that an actual payment--don't allow the clumping unless the
player appears to have enough points.

========================

Actually, here's an interesting question:  as Scorekeepor, I sometimes
get a request from the Speaker asking how many points a certain player
has.  The response is used to decide whether to allow the player to 
send points to the Vototron.

Now what if some monstrous CFJ goes through, affecting all the scores
retroactively in various ways?  Then it could happen that the information I 
gave to the Speaker is wrong, and a player gets to use the Vototron that 
shouldn't have. This could easily affect the outcome of a vote.

For certain decisions (like: Vototron, or the clumping payment),
could we maybe allow the Speaker to rely on best evidence (such as
the most recent undisputed Scorekeepor's report), and not have his 
decision changed even if the report was not quite correct?

Anyway, I do like Vanyel's idea.

Regards,
- elJefe

