PROTO-Proposal DB17 (Vanyel)
Proposal Limits
(Amends a Rule)

Amend [whatever the proposal rule is] to read:

Each Player shall have a Proposal queue.  Any time a Player sends a
Proposal to the Speaker, eir Proposal is added to eir queue.  The
maximum number of Proposals up for Vote at any time may not be 
more than the number of Active Players at the beginning of the
current Nomic Week.  Proposals are to be put up for Vote exactly
once a week, as soon as possible after the beginning of the Nomic
Week.  This takes precedence over any Rule which states otherwise.

If, when Proposals are being put up for vote, there are less than 
the maximum number of Proposals, then all will be cleared from the
Players' queues and added to the for-Vote queue.  If more than the
maximum are sent to the Speaker, then e shall go through the following
process to determine which Proposals are to be added to the for-Vote
queue:
     1)	E shall make a list of all Players in descending order by Honour.
     2)	E shall go through the list and remove all Players without any
	Proposals in eir queue.
     3) E shall go through the list in order, taking the first Proposal
	in the queue of each Player and adding it to the for-Vote queue
	until the for-Vote queue is full.
     4) If the Speaker completes the list, having taken one Proposal from
	each Player's Proposal queue, e shall return to Step 2 and repeat.
After the Speaker has determined which Proposals would go in the for-Vote
queue, e shall post the Proposals in the queue to the Public Forum and
clear the for-Vote queue.

The only way a Proposal may be prematurely removed from a Player's 
Proposal Queue is if e, the Player, specifically requests such to the
Speaker.  The Player may not replace a Proposal with another; if e
removes it from the queue, all lower positions move up one to clear
the hole.  Such a removal is irrevocable.

The Player may also request that a Proposal authored by eim
be removed from the Vote in the Public Forum; the Speaker shall post
a message to the Public Forum stating that said Proposal has been
removed from the Vote.  The Proposal is then discarded.  

[This allows people to replace Proposals already for Vote.  It does not,
however, confusingly renumber anything, or allow them to change the 
Proposal after it has been partially Voted on.  They may remove their
Proposal from the Vote, but must resubmit their revision at the end
of the queue.]

In certain special cases, a Player may want a block of Proposals to 
be certain of being proposed at the same time; this may be done by
sending a message to the Speaker requesting to "Clump" certain Proposals.
These Proposals *must* be adjacent in the Player's Proposal queue.
In order to Clump Proposals, a Player must pay 1 Pt. per Proposal for
less than 5 Proposals, 2 Pts. per Proposal for 5-10 Proposals, or
3 Pts. per Proposal for >10 Proposals.  No Clumps may be of more than
15 Proposals.  If the Speaker has received more than 30 requests and
is cycling through the Player's queues, and he comes across one proposal
of a Clump, all Proposals in the Clump shall be moved to the for-Vote
queue, unless that would put more than the maximum number of Proposals
in the queue, in which case *no* Proposals from the Clump shall be
added to the for-Vote queue.
***END PROTO

proposal history:
first proto 7 Oct 12:35 PM CDT
second proto 14 Oct 5:43 PM CDT

This should take care of all the limit problems.  Things to notice:
each player will have a chance at at *least* one Proposal, the people
who propose less are only shafted by *one*, the people who propose
most are the most honourable, Proposals cannot be removed by anyone
except the Player who proposed them, and that Player can remove them
at any time, "Clump"ing is tightly defined, the implementation of
"queues" is entirely up to the Speaker (i.e. could be entirely a mental
thing).

Comments, questions?

Vanyel

